t-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pit (Kid Icarus)|Pit]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kid Icarus]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rayman]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Rayman]]''\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Street Fighter]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Samus]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Metroid]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Sandbag\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Shadow the Hedgehog|Shadow]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sheik (Legend of Zelda)|Sheik]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Simon Belmont|Simon]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Castlevania]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sonic the Hedgehog|Sonic]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower|Tails]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Waluigi]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Wario]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[WarioWare]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Yoshi]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Yoshi]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Mega Man X|X]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|''[[Mega Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Young Link]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princess Zelda|Zelda]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Zero (Mega Man)|Zero]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Mega Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Zero Suit Samus]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Metroid]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|}\n\n== Development ==\nDevelopment of the original ''Super Smash Flash'' began around mid-2006, as Cleod9's first Flash game project on his then [[TI-89]]-centric website, McLeodGaming, after understanding Flash coding well enough to make a full-fledged game. Originally, the game was a combat-oriented platform game with a ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' fan-characters called \"Blade\" and \"Blue\" (whom would remain a playable character even in the final product) and the focus was to get through a large level with suspended platforms taking out flying robotic bees called Buzzers (enemies from the [[Sega Genesis]] game, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2]]'').{{Citation needed|date=September 2014}} The game was eventually reworked into a ''Super Smash Bros.'' fan game\u2014then early called a \"flash Smash engine\" by Cleod9\u2014where small updates began incorporating new content, be new playable characters, stages or items<ref name=about /> It was based on ''Super Smash Bros. Melee'' as that was the current title in the official series at the time. As Cleod9's first big flash project, the game was considered \"a great success for its time\".<ref>{{cite web|title=McLeodGaming \u2013 View Topic \u2013 SSF2 General Discussion [v0.9]|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=1171848#p1171848|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> The game was completed within roughly half a year's time without any outside coding assistance, and was released August 21, 2006 on ''Newgrounds'', a website known for its user-made Flash content.<ref>{{cite web|title =Game Projects <nowiki>|</nowiki> Greg McLeod|url = http://www.greg-mcleod.com/index.php/game/|publisher = McLeod, Gregory|accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> It is currently the 15th most played game ever on [[Newgrounds]].\n\n=== ''Super Smash Flash 2'' ===\nThe success of ''Super Smash Flash'' soon led to high demand for a sequel. When McLeodGaming first started development on ''Super Smash Flash 2'' in 2007, the game was planned to be a sequel to the original ''Super Smash Flash'', with the incremental aesthetic and gameplay improvements. This plan was ultimately discarded in favor of making a fresh, new start to reboot the series. Despite the title, ''Super Smash Flash 2'' is not actually a sequel; it is an entirely new game, and only retains the original name of the project because of how widely known the title has become throughout the fanbase. Although the game is not complete yet, pre-releases \u2013 also known as [[Game demo|demos]] of the game \u2013 have been posted to their website for users and fans to see how far in development the game is. Various attempts to post minor updates to the game have also been posted to the \"''Smash Flash DOJO''\", one of several websites run by developers based on a similar [[Nintendo]]-run site for the [[Super Smash Bros.|''Smash Bros.'']] series, but each attempt has been abandoned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the ''Smash Flash DOJO!!!''|url=http://ssfdojo.mcleodgaming.com/notices/notice-1|website=Smash Flash DOJO!!!|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref> Updates are also occasionally posted on the team's [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] pages.\n\nThere were two major turning points in the game's development. The first was on January 1, 2009, on the release of v0.4a. This was the point where the game began to sharply grow considerably more complex, leading to snags in development as the difficulty of adding new characters was stated by Cleod to have \"increased exponentially\" at this point.<ref>{{cite web|title=January 1, 2008 News (Happy New Year + v0.4a Released)|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=263180#p263180|website=McLeodGaming (1 January 2009)|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The second turning point came with the following release, v0.7, on January 1, 2011. Initially thought to merely be an update that added content, [[Final Fantasy character jobs#Black Mage|Black Mage]] was included as a [[Player character#hidden character|hidden character]] after playing ten battles. This was a shock to the fanbase, as he was the first character to be introduced who was not in the originally planned character roster. Directly related to knowledge of his surprise inclusion spreading among the general fanbase, McLeodGaming soon made an announcement that the oft-criticized planned roster had undergone a complete overhaul.<ref>{{cite web|title=January 6th, 2011 News (v0.7 Update + Important Roster Info)|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=904623#p904623|website=McLeodGaming (6 February 2011)|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe final demo, ''Super Smash Flash 2 Beta'', was announced on January 25, 2015. It was notable for dropping both the [[version number]] and designating itself as a [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta version]] rather than a [[Shareware|demo]]. On May 29, 2017, ''Super Smash Flash 2 Beta'' was finally released after three years of development, it added various aspects to stand on its own as a game, both present in the official ''Super Smash Bros.'' titles, such as Classic Mode (primarily in the vein of the original [[Super Smash Bros. (video game)|''Super Smash Bros.'']], but with added elements), and original to the game, such as Arena Mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Super Smash Flash'' garnered a mixed to positive critical reception. Though initially reviewed positively, later reviews such as one on FlashGN found the game to be \"lacking control\", and \"simply a buggy and flawed attempt at recreating one of the best fighting games of all time.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn|title=FGN- 'Super Smash Flash Review'|url=http://flashgn.com/review/2|publisher=Afro Ninja Productions|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref> Despite some poor reviews, Super Smash Flash earned a [[Newgrounds]] daily feature award, over 11 million views, and a four star rating, and later was categorized as making \"Flash Portal History\" for 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newgrounds.com/collection/flashportalhistory2006 |title=Flash Portal History: 2006 |publisher=[[Newgrounds]], Inc |access-date=24 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306045924/http://www.newgrounds.com/collection/flashportalhistory2006 |archive-date=6 March 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>  The game has picked up several other minor awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Smash Flash EXE Software Informer: Awards|url=http://super-smash-flash-exe.software.informer.com/awards/|publisher=[[Informer Technologies, Inc.]]|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Super Smash Flash 2'', though currently incomplete, has gained significantly more traction than its predecessor. It was featured in [[GamesRadar]]'s \"10 fan games that shouldn't be ceased or desisted\" as number 5 while still in its infancy, and gained a feature article on GoNintendo.<ref>{{cite web|author=RawmeatCowboy|title=''Super Smash Flash 2'' \u2013 fan-made game footage {{!}} GoNintendo \u2013 What are YOU waiting for?|url=http://gonintendo.com/?mode=viewstory&id=170019|publisher=GoNintendo|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Chiang|first=Oliver|title=10 fan games that shouldn't be ceased or desisted|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/10-fan-games-that-shouldnt-be-ceased-or-desisted/|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>  Shortly before the release of version 0.9b, one writer for the video gaming website [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] opined that \"There's a low-fi pixel art aesthetic and a sense of freedom that makes ''Super Smash Flash 2'' more appealing to me than the real thing.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Riendeau|first1=Danielle|title=Fan-made ''Smash Bros.'' has better characters|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/7/22/5927927/smash-bros-super-smash-flash-mario-zelda-chibi|website=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> ''Super Smash Flash 2'''s demos maintain over 400,000 plays a day on McLeodGaming alone, and peaked at over 1 million daily plays on January 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Facebook \u2013 Well, looks like we're going to have to amend Friday's post...|url=https://www.facebook.com/mcleodgaming/posts/10151409264220446|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>  Notably, the game's work-in-progress v0.9a demo was featured as an indie game at the worldwide ''Super Smash Bros.'' tournament [[Apex (tournament series)|Apex]] 2013, and returned the following two years with subsequent updates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indie Developers|url=http://www.apex-series.com/indie-developers/|publisher=Apex Series|access-date=24 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328011232/http://www.apex-series.com/indie-developers/ |archive-date=28 March 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n<references />\n\nhttp://urmomgei.com\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.supersmashflash.com/ Super Smash Flash website]\n* [http://mcleodgaming.com/ McLeodGaming website]\n* [http://ZacharyCorrellIsBad.com]\n{{Super Smash Bros. series}}\n{{Unofficial Mario media}}\n\n[[Category:Crossover video games]]\n[[Category:Action video games]]\n[[Category:Versus fighting games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Fangames]]\n[[Category:Flash games]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|SSF2|the Capcom video game|Super Street Fighter II}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| title = Super Smash Flash\n| image = Super Smash Flash logo.png\n| image_size= \n| caption = Logo for the original ''Super Smash Flash''\n| genre = [[Fighting game|Fighting]]\n| developer = SSF2 Team\n| publisher = McLeodGaming\n| creator = Gregory McLeod\n| platforms= [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]], [[Linux]], [[Adobe Flash]]\n| first release version = ''Super Smash Flash''\n| first release date = August 21, 2006\n| latest release version = Super Smash Flash 2 Beta 1.2.1.1\n| latest release date = March 19, 2020\n}}\n\n'''''Super Smash Flash''''' is a series of [[Fighting game|fighting]] [[browser game]]s published by [[Independent video game development|indie]] company McLeodGaming, led by Gregory McLeod under the alias Cleod9. It is based on the [[Super Smash Bros.|''Super Smash Bros'' series]].<ref name=about>{{cite web|last=McLeod|first=Gregory|title=McLeodGaming :: About|url=http://www.mcleodgaming.com/about.php|publisher=McLeodGaming|access-date=5 November 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020174406/http://www.mcleodgaming.com/about.php|archive-date=20 October 2012|df=}}</ref> The original ''Super Smash Flash'' is based specifically on ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]''. Its follow-up, also considered a reboot, is ''Super Smash Flash 2''.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:Super_Smash_Flash_2_Screenshot.png|left|frame|Screenshot of ''Super Smash Flash 2'', showing [[Mario]], [[Kirby (character)|Kirby]], [[Lloyd Irving]] and [[Ichigo Kurosaki]] fighting on the Battlefield stage.]]\nLike in the official ''Super Smash Bros.'' titles, the player's objective is to knock opponents off of the screen. Players are given a percentage counter instead of a health bar, which increases as they take damage. A higher damage percentage means that attacks will send the player farther, which may ultimately lead to a KO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Battling {{!}} Smash Flash DOJO!!!|url=http://ssfdojo.mcleodgaming.com/game-modes/battling/|work=Smash Flash DOJO!!!|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe games are not direct clones of the official titles, as they feature adjusted mechanics and playable content, both stages and characters, not present in the original ''Super Smash Bros.'' series by virtue of being a fanmade project.\n\nIn the original ''Super Smash Flash'', characters only have a total of five attacks each, activated by pressing the \"P\" key along with an arrow key, additionally, some characters had an extra attack while jumping. The reboot, ''Super Smash Flash 2'', offers control much more similar to that of the official games. Along with the option to use a keyboard like its predecessor, ''2'' adds support for [[USB]] [[Game controllers]] and other gaming devices that can be used for computers.\n\nAs with the official ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' games, both ''Super Smash Flash'' and ''Super Smash Flash 2'' include several single-player modes, such as campaigns to defeat a series of computer-controlled opponents, events that have specific goals to clear, mini-games to test the player, etc. Players are awarded with numerous rewards and other collectibles by clearing single-player modes.\n\nThe original game features three single-player modes. In Regular Match, players can choose between Classic and Adventure Modes; once the whole roster has been unlocked, All-Star Mode becomes available. In Stadium, several mini-games and challenges are pitched to the player such as destroying eight targets using each characters's own abilities in Target Test or defeating grey-shaded versions of the playable roster in Multi-Man Melee. In Training Mode, players can tune up their playing skills by setting several parameters of their own.\n\nThe reboot expands the single-player experience. Classic Mode, for instance, has a greater variety of opponents. For Stadium, Target Test has been renamed Target Smash and features two modes: the first is a general system that features several levels and difficulties with a set pattern for targets on each level, the second one is more similar to the original's system, in which each character has a specifically-designed, individual level that tests the character's own abilities to destroy the targets.<ref name=\"SSF2Beta\">{{cite web|title=YouTube - McLeodGaming Direct - Super Smash Flash 2 Beta (1/25/15)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6y4cX0jUxgI|website=YouTube|publisher=Google, Inc.|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> Multi-Man Melee is now called Multi-Man Smash and the player now confronts black-palette versions of [[Mario]], [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]], [[Kirby (character)|Kirby]] and [[Pikachu]], all whom have very limited movesets and high stamina. A missing Stadium sub-mode from the official games that is absent from the original ''SSF'' gets reincorporated: Home-Run Contest, where the objective is to launch as far as possible the Sandbag by previously racking up its damage, players are able to enable a disable a protective barrier that prevents the sandbag of getting out of the main platform, unless launched strong enough to break it. A new original Stadium sub-mode to be incorporated is Crystal Smash, where the objective is to destroy a multitude of crystals as quickly as possible. An Event Mode is also implemented, where players have to complete specific missions or defeat certain characters to accomplish the event; there is a total of 57 events to complete in the game.\n\n=== Multiplayer ===\nBoth ''Super Smash Flash'' and ''Super Smash Flash 2'' feature standard multiplayer battles, both against other players on the same machine and against computer-controlled characters with configurable difficulty levels.\n\nThe original game was very limited by its software Flash capacity; aside only one multiplayer mode (crowned as ''Melee'' mode), matches were limited for only two human players per match; the other remaining two slots could be filled with CPU entries only. The camera was only able to follow player one, leaving player two at a noticeable disadvantage.\n\n''SSF2'' expanded the multiplayer mode by introducing four player-entries controlled by human players and a dynamic camera system. Version 0.9b introduced Special Smash, a mode similar to the official ''Super Smash Bros.'' titles in which certain \"game modifiers\" like Mini (shrinks all characters), Slow (lowers the game speed), Turbo (which enables any attack to be cancelled on hit, directly taken with permission from fellow fan game [[Project M (video game)|''Project M'']]), or ''Super Smash Flash'' (which recreates the quirky and glitchy engine of the original game like attacks hitting once per frame, applying no hitlag, characters become unable to hold onto ledges, etc.) can be applied to matches.<ref name=kotaku>{{cite web|last1=Neltz|first1=Andr\u00e1s|title=The Smash Bros. Where You Can Play As Sora, Naruto, Ichigo, or Goku|url=http://kotaku.com/the-smash-bros-where-you-can-play-as-sora-goku-or-na-1609457769|website=Kotaku|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> The Beta version introduced an original mode called Arena Mode, which enabled players to participate in some mini-games playing with the existing physics and characters in unorthodox-for-the-series ways using the Sandbag, much like Stadium on the single-player mode. There are currently two sub-modes known. The first is called Sandbag Soccer, in which players are pitched in an enclosed stage sorted to two teams, red and blue, and have to get the Sandbag into the opposing team's goal. The first team that reaches the number of goals set prior to the match wins. The other is called Sandbag Basketball and features a similar premise to the latter, except players now have to get the Sandbag to pass through the opposing team's hoop to score.<ref name=\" SSF2Beta\"/>\n\nEver since demo version 0.9b of ''SSF2'', players can fight against opponents online through a proprietary system dubbed the \"McLeodGaming Network\".<ref name=kotaku /><ref>{{cite web|title=McLeodGaming Network|url=http://mgn.mcleodgaming.com/|website=McLeodGaming Network|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> Connections use the proprietary Adobe [[RTMFP]] technology unless the \"high latency\" setting is chosen, which hands the players off to a server rather than using a P2P connection.\n\n=== Playable characters ===\nThe original ''Super Smash Flash'' features 30 characters. These characters represent a wide variety of media, spanning not only video games but also manga, animated film, and fan-made creations. Like in the ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' series, a number of these characters must be \"unlocked\" through various means.\n\n''Super Smash Flash 2 Beta'' currently features 46 playable characters. As the game is still in development, this number is still subject to change. Fan-made newcomers from the previous game will not reappear due to the developers wanting to give a more professional tone to the game.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! width=175| Fighter\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:75px;\"| ''Flash''\n! style=\"text-align:center; width:75px;\"| ''Flash 2''\n! width=175| [[List of video game franchises|Franchise]] <!-- Use series indicated in the games; do not speculate -->\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[List of Kirby characters#Bandana Waddle Dee|Bandana Dee]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kirby (series)|Kirby]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Black Mage\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Final Fantasy]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Blade\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''McLeodGaming''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Blue\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Bomberman]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Bomberman]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Captain Falcon]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[F-Zero]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Chibi-Robo]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Chibi-Robo! (series)|Chibi-Robo!]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Cloud Strife|Cloud]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Final Fantasy]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Characters of Chrono Trigger#Crono|Crono]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Chrono (series)|Chrono]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Donkey Kong (character)|Donkey Kong]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Donkey Kong]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Falco Lombardi|Falco]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Star Fox]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Fox McCloud|Fox]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Goku]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Dragon Ball]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ichigo Kurosaki|Ichigo]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Bleach (manga)|Bleach]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Isaac (Golden Sun)|Isaac]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Golden Sun]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Inuyasha (character)|Inuyasha]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Inuyasha]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Jigglypuff]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Kirby (character)|Kirby]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kirby (series)|Kirby]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Knuckles the Echidna|Knuckles]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[List of Star Fox characters#Krystal|Krystal]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Star Fox]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Link (The Legend of Zelda)|Link]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Lloyd Irving|Lloyd]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Tales of Symphonia]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Lucario]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Luigi]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Luffy]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[One Piece]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mario]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Marth (Fire Emblem)|Marth]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Fire Emblem]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mega Man]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Mega Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Meta Knight]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kirby (series)|Kirby]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mewtwo]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mr. Game and Watch]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Game and Watch]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mr. Incredible]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[The Incredibles]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Naruto Uzumaki|Naruto]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Naruto]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ness (character)|Ness]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[EarthBound]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pac-Man]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Pac-Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princess Peach|Peach]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pichu]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pikachu]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Pok\u00e9mon]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pit (Kid Icarus)|Pit]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kid Icarus]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rayman]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Rayman]]''\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ryu (Street Fighter)|Ryu]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Street Fighter]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Samus]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Metroid]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| Sandbag\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Shadow the Hedgehog|Shadow]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sheik (Legend of Zelda)|Sheik]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Simon Belmont|Simon]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Castlevania]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sonic the Hedgehog|Sonic]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Miles \"Tails\" Prower|Tails]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Waluigi]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Super Mario]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Wario]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[WarioWare]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Yoshi]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Yoshi]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Mega Man X|X]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n|''[[Mega Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Young Link]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princess Zelda|Zelda]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Zero (Mega Man)|Zero]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| ''[[Mega Man]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Zero Suit Samus]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Metroid]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|}\n\n== Development ==\nDevelopment of the original ''Super Smash Flash'' began around mid-2006, as Cleod9's first Flash game project on his then [[TI-89]]-centric website, McLeodGaming, after understanding Flash coding well enough to make a full-fledged game. Originally, the game was a combat-oriented platform game with a ''Sonic the Hedgehog'' fan-characters called \"Blade\" and \"Blue\" (whom would remain a playable character even in the final product) and the focus was to get through a large level with suspended platforms taking out flying robotic bees called Buzzers (enemies from the [[Sega Genesis]] game, ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 2]]'').{{Citation needed|date=September 2014}} The game was eventually reworked into a ''Super Smash Bros.'' fan game\u2014then early called a \"flash Smash engine\" by Cleod9\u2014where small updates began incorporating new content, be new playable characters, stages or items<ref name=about /> It was based on ''Super Smash Bros. Melee'' as that was the current title in the official series at the time. As Cleod9's first big flash project, the game was considered \"a great success for its time\".<ref>{{cite web|title=McLeodGaming \u2013 View Topic \u2013 SSF2 General Discussion [v0.9]|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=1171848#p1171848|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> The game was completed within roughly half a year's time without any outside coding assistance, and was released August 21, 2006 on ''Newgrounds'', a website known for its user-made Flash content.<ref>{{cite web|title =Game Projects <nowiki>|</nowiki> Greg McLeod|url = http://www.greg-mcleod.com/index.php/game/|publisher = McLeod, Gregory|accessdate=26 March 2014}}</ref> It is currently the 15th most played game ever on [[Newgrounds]].\n\n=== ''Super Smash Flash 2'' ===\nThe success of ''Super Smash Flash'' soon led to high demand for a sequel. When McLeodGaming first started development on ''Super Smash Flash 2'' in 2007, the game was planned to be a sequel to the original ''Super Smash Flash'', with the incremental aesthetic and gameplay improvements. This plan was ultimately discarded in favor of making a fresh, new start to reboot the series. Despite the title, ''Super Smash Flash 2'' is not actually a sequel; it is an entirely new game, and only retains the original name of the project because of how widely known the title has become throughout the fanbase. Although the game is not complete yet, pre-releases \u2013 also known as [[Game demo|demos]] of the game \u2013 have been posted to their website for users and fans to see how far in development the game is. Various attempts to post minor updates to the game have also been posted to the \"''Smash Flash DOJO''\", one of several websites run by developers based on a similar [[Nintendo]]-run site for the [[Super Smash Bros.|''Smash Bros.'']] series, but each attempt has been abandoned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the ''Smash Flash DOJO!!!''|url=http://ssfdojo.mcleodgaming.com/notices/notice-1|website=Smash Flash DOJO!!!|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref> Updates are also occasionally posted on the team's [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] pages.\n\nThere were two major turning points in the game's development. The first was on January 1, 2009, on the release of v0.4a. This was the point where the game began to sharply grow considerably more complex, leading to snags in development as the difficulty of adding new characters was stated by Cleod to have \"increased exponentially\" at this point.<ref>{{cite web|title=January 1, 2008 News (Happy New Year + v0.4a Released)|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=263180#p263180|website=McLeodGaming (1 January 2009)|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The second turning point came with the following release, v0.7, on January 1, 2011. Initially thought to merely be an update that added content, [[Final Fantasy character jobs#Black Mage|Black Mage]] was included as a [[Player character#hidden character|hidden character]] after playing ten battles. This was a shock to the fanbase, as he was the first character to be introduced who was not in the originally planned character roster. Directly related to knowledge of his surprise inclusion spreading among the general fanbase, McLeodGaming soon made an announcement that the oft-criticized planned roster had undergone a complete overhaul.<ref>{{cite web|title=January 6th, 2011 News (v0.7 Update + Important Roster Info)|url=http://forums.mcleodgaming.com/viewtopic.php?p=904623#p904623|website=McLeodGaming (6 February 2011)|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe final demo, ''Super Smash Flash 2 Beta'', was announced on January 25, 2015. It was notable for dropping both the [[version number]] and designating itself as a [[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta version]] rather than a [[Shareware|demo]]. On May 29, 2017, ''Super Smash Flash 2 Beta'' was finally released after three years of development, it added various aspects to stand on its own as a game, both present in the official ''Super Smash Bros.'' titles, such as Classic Mode (primarily in the vein of the original [[Super Smash Bros. (video game)|''Super Smash Bros.'']], but with added elements), and original to the game, such as Arena Mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Super Smash Flash'' garnered a mixed to positive critical reception. Though initially reviewed positively, later reviews such as one on FlashGN found the game to be \"lacking control\", and \"simply a buggy and flawed attempt at recreating one of the best fighting games of all time.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Shawn|title=FGN- 'Super Smash Flash Review'|url=http://flashgn.com/review/2|publisher=Afro Ninja Productions|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref> Despite some poor reviews, Super Smash Flash earned a [[Newgrounds]] daily feature award, over 11 million views, and a four star rating, and later was categorized as making \"Flash Portal History\" for 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newgrounds.com/collection/flashportalhistory2006 |title=Flash Portal History: 2006 |publisher=[[Newgrounds]], Inc |access-date=24 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306045924/http://www.newgrounds.com/collection/flashportalhistory2006 |archive-date=6 March 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>  The game has picked up several other minor awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Super Smash Flash EXE Software Informer: Awards|url=http://super-smash-flash-exe.software.informer.com/awards/|publisher=[[Informer Technologies, Inc.]]|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Super Smash Flash 2'', though currently incomplete, has gained significantly more traction than its predecessor. It was featured in [[GamesRadar]]'s \"10 fan games that shouldn't be ceased or desisted\" as number 5 while still in its infancy, and gained a feature article on GoNintendo.<ref>{{cite web|author=RawmeatCowboy|title=''Super Smash Flash 2'' \u2013 fan-made game footage {{!}} GoNintendo \u2013 What are YOU waiting for?|url=http://gonintendo.com/?mode=viewstory&id=170019|publisher=GoNintendo|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Chiang|first=Oliver|title=10 fan games that shouldn't be ceased or desisted|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/10-fan-games-that-shouldnt-be-ceased-or-desisted/|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=5 November 2012}}</ref>  Shortly before the release of version 0.9b, one writer for the video gaming website [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] opined that \"There's a low-fi pixel art aesthetic and a sense of freedom that makes ''Super Smash Flash 2'' more appealing to me than the real thing.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Riendeau|first1=Danielle|title=Fan-made ''Smash Bros.'' has better characters|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/7/22/5927927/smash-bros-super-smash-flash-mario-zelda-chibi|website=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref> ''Super Smash Flash 2'''s demos maintain over 400,000 plays a day on McLeodGaming alone, and peaked at over 1 million daily plays on January 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Facebook \u2013 Well, looks like we're going to have to amend Friday's post...|url=https://www.facebook.com/mcleodgaming/posts/10151409264220446|publisher=McLeodGaming|accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref>  Notably, the game's work-in-progress v0.9a demo was featured as an indie game at the worldwide ''Super Smash Bros.'' tournament [[Apex (tournament series)|Apex]] 2013, and returned the following two years with subsequent updates.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indie Developers|url=http://www.apex-series.com/indie-developers/|publisher=Apex Series|access-date=24 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328011232/http://www.apex-series.com/indie-developers/ |archive-date=28 March 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.supersmashflash.com/ Super Smash Flash website]\n* [http://mcleodgaming.com/ McLeodGaming website]\n\n{{Super Smash Bros. series}}\n{{Unofficial Mario media}}\n\n[[Category:Crossover video games]]\n[[Category:Action video games]]\n[[Category:Versus fighting games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Fangames]]\n[[Category:Flash games]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros.]]\n", "name_user": "139.130.58.154", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Smash_Flash"}
